column35:
Not Swabbed, Oiseau trouvé mort au bord du fleuve, à la Réserve Naturelle de la rivière Fouquette. Le cadavre était frais, mais des visiteurs avec un chien ont abimé la carcasse.
Autre observation la semaine précédente (lundi le 23 mai) :Harelde kakawi observé de très près en kayakant à l'embouchure de la rivière Fouquette. L'oiseau semblait fatigué, étrangement peu peureux. Il dormait sur l'eau alors que nous passions à moins de 3 mètres avec deux embarcations. Au retour, il était installé pour se reposer sur la berge et à mis beaucoup trop de temps pour un oiseau en bonne santé pour rejoindre l'eau. Les Harelde kakawi, selon mon expérience (15 ans à travailler dans le Grand Nord) sont très frileux des humains. Celui-ci avait définitivement un comportement différent. Des plumes ont été retrouvées sur la berge la même journée que l'Eider. Elles pourraient correspondre au plumage du Kakawi, mais sans certitude.

column2: Sur le fleuve St-Laurent près des rives , dans une anse à marée haute (probablement que les carcasses ont été emportées par la marée).
column35: Not Swabbed, J'ai observé plus d'une douzaine de carcasses flottant sur le fleuve St-Laurent lors d'une balade en kayak. J'en ai observé aussi 2-3 les autres journées (j'ai été 18 jours en tout dans le secteur). Ça fait plus de 12 ans que je pagaie à cet endroit et il ne m'est jamais arrivé de voir autant d'oiseaux marins morts en même temps. Habituellement, j'en vois 1 ou 2 dans mon été. J'étais au camping Paradis Marin à Grandes-Bergeronnes (Côte-Nord, Québec).

Je pense que ce serait la grippe aviaire mais c'est sûre que je ne peux évidemment rien garantir.

column2: Herring Cove Beach, Champney's Arm (connecting to fox island), Port Rexton, NL
column35:
Not Swabbed, I have seen an increasing number of dead or sick common murre's in Port Rexton, NL, over the last few weeks (I have never previously seen them on the beach, and visit the area daily). Today I saw one live (but sick looking bird), on the side of the road. Yesterday I saw two live (but sick looking birds) on the beach. There are also approximately 5 dead birds on the beach at present.
I did a full survey of the beach, after seeing your email, to take some pictures.
Addition to report: There were a total of 13 dead murres and 3 dead garnets, plus one living but sick looking gannet. I've attached photos to support identification. I was walking a near bt trail and saw 2 other dead murres - i suspect I'd continue to find more if I kept looking.

column2: Au village de Barachois-de-Malbaie (grand Perce), a partir du stationnement de la halte routiere de la plage a l'est du viaduc du train. En descendant les marches, on marche pres de la mer, vers l'ouest (gauche) et en marchant jusqu'au pont du train, on rencontre facilement les 3 oiseaux, l'un apres l'autre. Ce n'est pas une grande distance (10 minutes de marche totale)
column35:
Not Swabbed, À la plage de Barachois de Malbaie, a partir de la halte routiere (petit stationnement, pres du viaduc de train), en Gaspesie, Quebec.
En marchant a la plage, nous avons croise un oiseau mort, qui semblait être un fou de bassan mort, vu l'envergure et la couleur des ailes, mais son visage et son corps etaient manges, donc l'identification etait difficile.
2 minutes plus loin, il y avait un oiseau brun, avec un bec de canard, mort aussi.
et 5 minutes plus loin, pres du pont de train, un goeland argente mort.
Comme il est suggere de declarer les oiseaux sauvages morts, a cause de la grippe aviaire, je suis venue ici ecrire.
En esperant que c'est le bon canaux.
Les oiseaux morts sont presentement accessibles aux autres oiseaux, qui pourraient être infectes a leur tour.

Penny was driving along the highway through Arisaig on her way to work in Stellarton when she noticed a Gannet on the road she stopped and picked it up using a bag she had in her vehicle. When she picked it up the Gannet bit her and broke the skin. She carried on with the rescue and placed it in the back seat of her car on the rubber floor mat. She drove to Stellarton and then was told to call us by a fellow employee. She had heard about AI but had not heard not to handle birds due to it. She cleaned her wound as soon as she got to work. When she called me I sent someone out to collect the bird following all AI protocols and the bird was euthanized and will be sent for testing. I spoke to Penny and let her know that we can contract AI from the birds and that I would be calling Public Health on her behalf as soon as I got back to the office. When I called Public Health they already knew about the case as Penny called herself. She also went out and got the flu shot for this season as a co worker had thought it might help. I will be following up with Penny and she knows what symptoms to watch for. Carcass Temporarily Retained (Office) NA NA

column35: Not Swabbed, A white cormorant bird was on the beach shore (Salmon Beach, NB), alive and alert (from what I could ascertain) but sitting as the tide was coming in. It would extend its wings and get up on its legs and move forward a bit as the water would hit it but then it would sit back down again. I called the local Department of Natural Resources and two rangers came and took it away. They indicated that it would be euthenized as to end any suffering and prevent spread. I am left wondering if we had let it be, would it have been fine and recovered? I was at odds with bringing in human intervention and causing it distress. I could not find any information online to indicate if it would have been fine and recovered.

column2: Herring Cove Beach, Champney's Arm, Port Rexton
column35:
Not Swabbed, Today I saw three dead northern gannet's on the beach in Champney's Arm (Port Rexton, NL), as well as one living gannet on the short that didn't seem well. I saw a second live gannet (that didn't seem in good health) on the side of the road on Robbin Hood Beach (port rexton, NL). Over the last week, I have also seen an increasing number of dead and sick common murres (I will report these in a separate post). I have never previously seen either of these birds on the shore. Here is the exact location: https://www.google.com/maps/place/Champney's+Arm,+Port+Rexton,+NL+A0C+2H0/@48.3871182,-53.317102,16z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x4b74f641e5919bf5:0x7ca8664cf95f4fbe!8m2!3d48.391648!4d-53.3072319. Here is the location of the second northern gannet: https://www.google.com/maps/place/Champney's+Arm,+Port+Rexton,+NL+A0C+2H0/@48.394675,-53.3255519,16z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x4b74f641e5919bf5:0x7ca8664cf95f4fbe!8m2!3d48.391648!4d-53.3072319
Follow up report: I did a full survey of the beach, after seeing your email, to take some pictures.
There were a total of 13 dead murres and 3 dead garnets, plus one living but sick looking gannet. I've attached photos to support identification. I was walking a near bt trail and saw 2 other dead murres - i suspect I'd continue to find more if I kept looking.

I first observed possibly disease gulls on Bear Island in 2022 on 11 August. At a distance, I observed adult and grown hatch year Herring Gulls exhibiting signs of neurological disease. This visit was short and included some young children and I did not feel it safe to mix a closer look at diseased birds into the visit.

I visited again on 3 September, this time prepared to safely gather some samples if need be. My report on this visit is attached. The samples were received by provincial wildlife officers at their office in Cornwallis Park. However, I do not know if these samples were tested for influenza. As of early June, the annual budget for wildlife disease diagnostic testing had been expended due to massive demands associated with the influenza outbreak. It would have been a prudent management decision to assume the Bear Island birds were infected and not to spend almost non-existent resources on additional testing. AI was all over the region by then. You can follow up on this with CWHC-Atlantic Region in PEI.
Any estimate of actual mortality will be +/- 500% . On 3 September, I found the bones of birds the size of downy chicks up to fully-grown (relative to Herring Gulls). We have no accurate census of nesting gulls on Bear Island but, from counts of adults clustering on the near-shore water in spring when disturbed by people on the island, I guestimate there are often between 400-500 nesting pairs of Herring Gulls and an equal number of Greater Black-backed Gulls. Most of the carcass remains from dead birds on the beach would have washed away by the time I visited the island on 3 September. The on-land nesting area used especially by Herring Gulls was totally overgrown by dense vegetation by then also, so it was impossible to know if carcasses were widely present across this nesting area. The bones of the carcasses that remained on the beach mostly were not fresh and had fallen between beach rocks, thus securing them from being washed away immediately. I think an estimate of 20% all-age population mortality might be conservative but not too far off what really happened. So, 1000 pairs of adult gulls, 1.?? hatch year birds per nest attempt surviving to 3 September might add up to 20% of about 3000 birds = 600 dead?

Not Swabbed, A large bird flew into our window and died shortly after, the bird had been spotted hanging around a tree very close to the window for several weeks, eating the leaves from the trees. When the bird hit the window very hard, its stomach burst open through its skin and under a wing. The leaves it consumed had been ejected from the stomach with many still projecting out from the wound. It seemed to be an alarming amount of relatively freshly eaten leaves that would have strained on the stomach lining. The bird was placed in the garage to be buried the next day, but we wanted to submit this report just in case there was any concern or interest in examining the body,

column35:
Not Swabbed, Estimated about 6 dead gulls (herring and ring bill gulls) and 1 very visibly sick gull in a stretch of beach about 100ft long on Green Island (Bay of Islands Region). These observations were made while we were setting up song bird recorders on the beach (QFN) and was only a quick snap shot of what was present as we didn't want to spend more time than necessary in the area. This was also only on a very small portion of the island, so the numbers provided are estimates. Total healthy is just an estimate of gulls in total, there is a whole colony on the island. There are also Cormorants and Guillemonts present.
Note: Responded with photos:  "The first photo is the juvenile with a herring that appeared sick. The others are of the live birds on the island, we didnt get any of the dead birds. "

column35: Un pygargue à tête blanche a été trouvé vivant dans la forêt d'un particulier le à Sainte-Béatrix.L'oiseau se tenait le cou mou et il a été facilement attrapé. Monsieur Jacques Lessard du Centre Refuge Nymous est allé capturer l'oiseau pour l'apporter à leur refuge. Une bénévole de l'UQROP, Marie-Claude Nadeau a effectué le transport de l'oiseau de Joliette à Saint-Hyacinthe. à l'admission à la Clinique des oiseaux de proie, les Docteures Claire Grosset et Julie Pujol ont constaté des signes neurologiques compatibles avec l'influenza aviaire (absence mentale, syndrome vestibulaire, tête penchée et tremblements incontrôlés). L'oiseau n'a pas été examiné, ni hébergé dans une cage ou une volière. Il a été euthanasié dans le local de quarantaine sans contact avec d'autres oiseaux.

column35:
Three hatch year gull carcasses (portions) were found on Bear Island in Annapolis Basin, NS on September 3, 2022. Birds with neurological signs and carcass scavenging were noted at location on Aug. 11, 2022 by the submitter. Returned to investigate and secure samples on Sept. 3. Bear Island is a nest colony for ~400 herring gulls, ~400 great black-backed gulls, ~300 double-crested cormorants, ~30 great blue herons and 100 banks swallows.
Note: specimen #1 and #3 were combination swabs, specimen #2 was oral swab only (DJ).
